@Thobela-h3x Two important things:
1 - I think the reason we let Barney off the hook is that what he does is so outlandish, it's impossible to take seriously. He doesn't seem like a real person in a show that feels real and grounded; he's a cartoon character. I completely understand how somebody could watch HIMYM and think that Ted sucks and Barney doesn't: Ted feels shitty in a very real way and probably reminds you of somebody you know, while Barney is a cartoon character.
2 - You don't need "consent", you need "*informed* consent". Which is why Barney's deceptions (if taken at face value, in defiance of my previous point) is absolutely rape.

@dolphinswilltakeover No, I think I understand and agree with their point. I think you're dismissing their point with a long-winded "it's not that deep" expression about real life. There absolutely are conscious decisions being made in real life about things that might signal something or other about the environment or society, that you can observe and notice.

Have you ever asked yourself why we put certain decorations during certain events, but not others? For a very simple, clear cut example, why do we put primarily western/christian based imagery out and about during Christmas, but we tend to not have eastern style decorations? That signals something about our society - it's not inherently good or bad, but it's something that can be observed and analyzed. Why is a pedestrian crossing on the road at a particular position, and not another position? Even individuals, the way they dress, or walk, or talk, they also signal things about themselves. There is a certain level of intentionality in their "unintentionality", so to speak. One obviously can't use this to stereotype and pigeonhole whole groups of people into behaviours or societal roles, but it can still be observed, and this can lead to better understanding of each other if used correctly.

Now obviously people in all times have tended to seek to subvert any such observations, so the value of commentary based on observations can be fleeting. But that's getting into deeper weeds than I've already gotten into to explain my own understanding.

