@MsLilly200 "Fun and enjoyment" are benefits. I should preface that my question isn't an attack on anyone who likes whatever they like. It's why I wrote "genuinely." 

If people didn't get something out of an experience they likely won't want to do it again. If people are getting some enjoyment from otherwise irredeemably evil characters, that's fine. This video tries to say more than that though. At some points she compartmentalizes the desire to enjoy bad things by saying "it's good actually because it can teach us something about ourselves and about how we interact with society." Okay, then what (aside from just generally liking it) does it teach you about yourself that you like hot guys covered in blood? What does excusing a rapist because he's charming mean about someone's psyche?

That's the full context of my question. "What is the genuine benefit of liking characters like this (outside of just  vaguely enjoying it)?" What is the deeper psychology there? I think that's fascinating and fun to extrapolate on.
